1
00:00:00,160 --> 00:00:05,640
Price action is often overcomplicated, 
and even confusing for many traders. 

2
00:00:05,640 --> 00:00:12,360
Well, Heiken Ashi candles simplify everything.
Pay attention because THIS will be your ultimate  

3
00:00:12,360 --> 00:00:20,320
price action guide, using Heiken Ashi candles!
 
So Heiken Ashi candles offer a unique way to view  

4
00:00:20,320 --> 00:00:26,200
price action, helping you spot trends 
and remove a lot of the market noise. 

5
00:00:26,200 --> 00:00:29,960
They differ quite a lot from 
traditional candlesticks. 

6
00:00:29,960 --> 00:00:36,280
Traditional candlesticks show the open, high, 
low, and close prices for a given time period. 

7
00:00:36,280 --> 00:00:41,560
Heiken Ashi candles, on the other hand, 
use a different calculation method. 

8
00:00:41,560 --> 00:00:47,120
This method smooths out price 
information, making trends easier to spot. 

9
00:00:47,120 --> 00:00:51,840
The main difference lies in how 
Heiken Ashi candles are calculated. 

10
00:00:51,840 --> 00:00:56,400
Heiken Ashi uses averages.
This averaging process creates a smoother  

11
00:00:56,400 --> 00:01:02,300
price chart, filtering out some of the noise 
that can make traditional charts harder to read.
  

12
00:01:02,300 --> 00:01:08,160
Heiken Ashi candles have unique colors and 
shapes that tell you about market trends. 

13
00:01:08,160 --> 00:01:12,920
In an uptrend, Heiken Ashi candles 
often appear as a series of green  

14
00:01:12,920 --> 00:01:19,240
candles with small or no lower wicks.
In a downtrend, you'll see a series of  

15
00:01:19,240 --> 00:01:25,720
red candles with small or no upper wicks.
 
The color of a Heiken Ashi candle tells you  

16
00:01:25,720 --> 00:01:32,440
about the overall direction of price movement.
A green candle implies upward movement, while a  

17
00:01:32,440 --> 00:01:36,880
red one indicates downward movement. 
 
The size of the candle body  

18
00:01:36,880 --> 00:01:41,920
shows the strength of the move.
A large body means a strong move,  

19
00:01:41,920 --> 00:01:48,520
while a small body implies a weaker move.
 
Heiken Ashi candles also have wicks,  

20
00:01:48,520 --> 00:01:52,760
just like traditional candlesticks.
These wicks can give you clues  

21
00:01:52,760 --> 00:01:58,480
about potential trend changes.
A long lower wick on a red candle might  

22
00:01:58,480 --> 00:02:05,280
suggest that buyers are starting to enter the 
market, potentially signaling a trend reversal.
  

23
00:02:05,280 --> 00:02:12,680
In a strong uptrend, you might see a long series 
of green candles with little to no lower wicks. 

24
00:02:12,680 --> 00:02:19,200
This pattern is much clearer on a Heiken Ashi 
chart than on a traditional candlestick chart.
  

25
00:02:19,200 --> 00:02:24,160
Heiken Ashi candles can help you stay in 
trends longer, because they filter out  

26
00:02:24,160 --> 00:02:30,160
some of the minor price fluctuations, that 
might shake you out of a trade too early. 

27
00:02:30,160 --> 00:02:35,600
When using these candles, you might notice 
that trends appear to last longer and  

28
00:02:35,600 --> 00:02:41,280
reversals seem less frequent compared 
to traditional candlestick charts.
  

29
00:02:41,280 --> 00:02:47,480
Now, Heiken Ashi candles aren't perfect.
Because they use averaged prices, they can  

30
00:02:47,480 --> 00:02:53,240
sometimes lag behind real-time price movements.
This means that while they're great for  

31
00:02:53,240 --> 00:02:57,640
finding trends, they might not 
be the best tool for pinpointing  

32
00:02:57,640 --> 00:03:03,960
exact entry and exit points for trades.
 
One key difference between Heiken Ashi and  

33
00:03:03,960 --> 00:03:10,800
traditional candlesticks is how they handle gaps.
Because Heiken Ashi uses averaged values,  

34
00:03:10,800 --> 00:03:17,720
it doesn't show gaps between trading sessions.
This can be both an advantage and a disadvantage,  

35
00:03:17,720 --> 00:03:21,800
depending on your trading style.
If you're trading a market where  

36
00:03:21,800 --> 00:03:28,920
gaps are important, like stocks or forex, you 
might want to use Heiken Ashi in combination  

37
00:03:28,920 --> 00:03:31,880
with traditional candlestick charts.
 
How to analyze price action

38
00:03:31,880 --> 00:03:38,520
When reading Heiken Ashi candles, you need to 
pay close attention to several key aspects. 

39
00:03:38,520 --> 00:03:44,520
First, you look at the candle color.
In Heiken Ashi charts, green candles  

40
00:03:44,520 --> 00:03:51,000
typically represent bullish movement, while 
red candles indicate bearish movement.
  

41
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:54,880
The color of the candle tells you 
about the overall direction of  

42
00:03:54,880 --> 00:04:00,040
price movement during that period.
A green candle means the closing  

43
00:04:00,040 --> 00:04:05,400
price was higher than the opening 
price, so this means buying pressure. 

44
00:04:05,400 --> 00:04:10,480
A red candle shows that the closing 
price was lower than the opening price,  

45
00:04:10,480 --> 00:04:14,800
indicating selling pressure.
 
Next, you pay attention to the  

46
00:04:14,800 --> 00:04:18,720
size of the candle body.
Larger bodies indicate  

47
00:04:18,720 --> 00:04:24,160
stronger moves in the market.
A candle with a large body shows that there was  

48
00:04:24,160 --> 00:04:31,200
a significant price movement during that period.
In an uptrend, a large green candle implies  

49
00:04:31,200 --> 00:04:35,200
strong buying pressure.
In a downtrend, a large red  

50
00:04:35,200 --> 00:04:40,840
candle indicates strong selling pressure.
 
 
The size of the body compared to previous  

51
00:04:40,840 --> 00:04:45,840
candles can also give you clues about 
the strength of the current trend. 

52
00:04:45,840 --> 00:04:50,320
If you see a series of candles with 
progressively larger bodies of the same  

53
00:04:50,320 --> 00:04:56,720
color, it often indicates a strengthening 
trend. This means increased momentum.
  

54
00:04:56,720 --> 00:05:03,200
You can also easily find instances of loss 
of momentum. Like in this example, where the  

55
00:05:03,200 --> 00:05:09,600
market was in a downtrend and the candlesticks 
started to become smaller and more uneven. 

56
00:05:09,600 --> 00:05:16,040
This is the first sign that the downtrend is 
losing strength and a trend change is coming.
 
  

57
00:05:16,040 --> 00:05:22,000
The presence or absence of wicks on Heiken 
Ashi candles is another factor to consider. 

58
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:26,080
Wicks can tell you a lot about the 
price action during that period. 
  

59
00:05:26,080 --> 00:05:32,400
Long wicks, on the other hand, can indicate 
potential reversals or indecision in the market. 

60
00:05:32,400 --> 00:05:38,200
A long upper wick on a red candle or a 
long lower wick on a green candle might  

61
00:05:38,200 --> 00:05:43,440
show that the current trend is losing 
steam and a reversal could be coming.
  

62
00:05:43,440 --> 00:05:49,200
Large wicks can indicate a high level of 
volatility or uncertainty in the market. 

63
00:05:49,200 --> 00:05:54,600
If the high and low prices for a particular 
time frame are significantly different from  

64
00:05:54,600 --> 00:05:58,680
the open and close prices, it may 
indicate that there was a lot of  

65
00:05:58,680 --> 00:06:05,240
buying and selling activity during that period.
This could be a sign that the market is indecisive  

66
00:06:05,240 --> 00:06:11,080
or that there is a lack of clear direction.
On the other hand, if the wicks are small or  

67
00:06:11,080 --> 00:06:15,360
absent, it may indicate that 
the market is more stable
  

68
00:06:15,360 --> 00:06:20,760
Consecutive candlesticks with long wicks on 
a Heiken Ashi chart is something you should  

69
00:06:20,760 --> 00:06:26,040
paying attention to, because this can 
potentially indicate a change in trend. 

70
00:06:26,040 --> 00:06:31,120
When these wicks overlap, they create 
a price zone that is likely to exhibit  

71
00:06:31,120 --> 00:06:35,760
buying or selling pressure.
 
Changes in the candle color  

72
00:06:35,760 --> 00:06:41,800
are also important to watch for.
A shift from a series of one color to another,  

73
00:06:41,800 --> 00:06:46,760
might signal a potential trend change.
For example, if you've been seeing a  

74
00:06:46,760 --> 00:06:53,520
long series of green candles and suddenly a 
big red candle appears, it could be an early  

75
00:06:53,520 --> 00:06:59,560
warning sign of a trend reversal.
 
However, with Heiken Ashi candles,  

76
00:06:59,560 --> 00:07:05,360
trend changes often appear more gradually 
than with traditional candlesticks. 

77
00:07:05,360 --> 00:07:12,760
You might see a few small bodied candles of the 
opposite color before a full reversal takes place. 

78
00:07:12,760 --> 00:07:18,360
This can actually be an advantage, as it can 
help you avoid getting shaken out of trades  

79
00:07:18,360 --> 00:07:22,388
by minor price fluctuations.
 
 
Heiken Ashi market structure

80
00:07:22,388 --> 00:07:25,920
Heiken Ashi candles make market 
structure easier to read. 

81
00:07:25,920 --> 00:07:31,520
In an uptrend, these candles have no 
lower shadows when the trend is strong. 

82
00:07:31,520 --> 00:07:35,960
This means the low of each 
candle is the same as its open. 

83
00:07:35,960 --> 00:07:40,240
You see a row of green candles 
with only upper shadows. 

84
00:07:40,240 --> 00:07:43,520
This pattern tells you buyers are in control.
  

85
00:07:43,520 --> 00:07:49,320
As the uptrend goes on, each green candle's 
high is usually higher than the last. 

86
00:07:49,320 --> 00:07:57,120
This creates higher highs. At the same time, 
each candle opens higher. This forms higher lows. 

87
00:07:57,120 --> 00:08:02,720
These higher highs and higher lows 
are the building blocks of an uptrend. 

88
00:08:02,720 --> 00:08:09,280
When the uptrend starts to weaken, you might 
see small lower shadows on the green candles. 

89
00:08:09,280 --> 00:08:12,880
This is a hint that sellers 
are starting to push back. 

90
00:08:12,880 --> 00:08:17,080
It's not time to sell yet, but 
it's time to pay attention.
  

91
00:08:17,080 --> 00:08:24,400
In a downtrend, things flip. You see red candles 
with lower shadows, but no upper shadows. 

92
00:08:24,400 --> 00:08:32,240
This shows a strong downtrend. Each red candle's 
low is lower than the last, making lower lows. 

93
00:08:32,240 --> 00:08:38,880
The highs are also dropping, forming lower highs.
 
Sometimes, the market takes a break from  

94
00:08:38,880 --> 00:08:44,480
trending. This is called consolidation.
With Heiken Ashi candles, you'll see a  

95
00:08:44,480 --> 00:08:49,040
mix of red and green candles.
Often, these candles have  

96
00:08:49,040 --> 00:08:53,680
both upper and lower shadows.
The highs and lows stay about  

97
00:08:53,680 --> 00:08:58,040
the same, making a range.
 
Heiken Ashi candles can help  

98
00:08:58,040 --> 00:09:03,040
you spot when a trend might change.
If you've seen lots of green candles  

99
00:09:03,040 --> 00:09:08,360
in an uptrend, and suddenly there's 
a red candle with no upper shadow,  

100
00:09:08,360 --> 00:09:13,680
the trend might be about to reverse. 
 
When looking at market structure with Heiken  

101
00:09:13,680 --> 00:09:21,640
Ashi candles, watch the size of the candles too.
In a strong trend, the candles tend to be bigger. 

102
00:09:21,640 --> 00:09:25,840
This shows price is moving 
more in the trend's direction. 

103
00:09:25,840 --> 00:09:30,760
If the candles start getting smaller, 
the trend might be losing steam.
  

104
00:09:30,760 --> 00:09:37,160
Also, look at how many candles of the same 
color appear in a row. A long string of green  

105
00:09:37,160 --> 00:09:42,080
candles shows a strong uptrend.
A long string of red candles  

106
00:09:42,080 --> 00:09:45,560
shows a strong downtrend.
When you start seeing more  

107
00:09:45,560 --> 00:09:50,720
switches between red and green, the 
trend might be weakening or changing.
  

108
00:09:50,720 --> 00:09:55,600
Heiken Ashi candles can help you find 
support and resistance levels too. 

109
00:09:55,600 --> 00:09:59,320
In an uptrend, old broken 
highs tend to act as support. 

110
00:10:00,160 --> 00:10:05,240
In a downtrend, old broken 
lows often act as resistance. 

111
00:10:05,240 --> 00:10:11,920
These levels are key parts of market structure.
 
 
The sequence of price swings is also important. 

112
00:10:11,920 --> 00:10:16,760
A swing high happens when price 
reaches a peak and starts to fall. 

113
00:10:16,760 --> 00:10:21,840
A swing low is when price hits 
a low point and starts to rise. 

114
00:10:21,840 --> 00:10:26,360
These swings show where buyers and 
sellers are fighting for control.
  

115
00:10:26,360 --> 00:10:31,600
In an uptrend, you'll see swing lows 
getting higher over time. Each new  

116
00:10:31,600 --> 00:10:36,160
low is higher than the last.
Buyers are getting stronger. 

117
00:10:36,160 --> 00:10:42,960
At the same time, swing highs are also rising. 
Each new high is higher than the one before.
  

118
00:10:42,960 --> 00:10:48,520
In a downtrend, it's the opposite. 
Swing highs get lower over time. 

119
00:10:48,520 --> 00:10:53,320
Each new high is lower than the 
last. Sellers are in control. 

120
00:10:53,320 --> 00:10:59,680
Swing lows also keep getting lower.
 
Sometimes, swing highs or lows  

121
00:10:59,680 --> 00:11:05,440
bunch up at the same level. We call 
these equal highs or equal lows. They're  

122
00:11:05,440 --> 00:11:11,080
important because they show areas where 
price had trouble moving past before.
  

123
00:11:11,080 --> 00:11:16,640
Watching how these swings form and change 
can tell you a lot about market strength. 

124
00:11:16,640 --> 00:11:21,520
If swings are getting bigger, it 
might mean the trend is gaining power. 

125
00:11:21,520 --> 00:11:25,880
If they're getting smaller, the 
trend might be losing steam.
  

126
00:11:25,880 --> 00:11:31,520
Speed matters too. Quick, sharp swings 
often mean more power behind the move. 

127
00:11:31,520 --> 00:11:36,248
Slow, gradual swings might 
mean the trend is weaker.
 
  

128
00:11:36,248 --> 00:11:38,480
HA Support and resistance
Heiken Ashi candles can help  

129
00:11:38,480 --> 00:11:44,480
spot major support and resistance levels 
through color changes and wick patterns. 

130
00:11:44,480 --> 00:11:50,640
When candles change their color and form wicks, 
it often happens at support or resistance.
  

131
00:11:50,640 --> 00:11:55,640
With Heiken Ashi, you might see 
red candles turn green at support. 

132
00:11:55,640 --> 00:12:01,320
This shows buyers stepping in.
So, price is falling with red candles. Then,  

133
00:12:01,320 --> 00:12:08,000
at a past price level, the candles turn green. 
 
You might also see green candles turn red at  

134
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:15,360
resistance. This shows sellers taking control.
For instance, price is rising with green candles.  

135
00:12:15,360 --> 00:12:19,000
Then, at a past resistance, 
the candles turn red. 
  

136
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:24,720
A long lower wick, on a green candle, 
at support, shows strong buying. 

137
00:12:24,720 --> 00:12:31,080
A long upper wick, on a red candle, 
at resistance, shows strong selling.
  

138
00:12:31,080 --> 00:12:36,920
For example, price approaches this support level.
You see a red Heiken Ashi candle  

139
00:12:36,920 --> 00:12:40,480
with a long lower wick.
The next candle is green.  

140
00:12:40,480 --> 00:12:47,560
This pattern implies support was held. The 
long wick shows buyers stepped in at the low.
  

141
00:12:47,560 --> 00:12:55,200
At resistance, you might see a green candle with 
a long upper wick, followed by a red candle. This  

142
00:12:55,200 --> 00:13:01,680
pattern implies resistance held. The long 
wick shows sellers came in at the high.
  

143
00:13:01,680 --> 00:13:06,960
Sometimes, you'll see a "spinning top" 
Heiken Ashi candle at a major level. 

144
00:13:06,960 --> 00:13:11,800
This is a candle with a small 
body and long wicks on both sides. 

145
00:13:11,800 --> 00:13:15,720
It shows indecision.
If this appears at a key level,  

146
00:13:15,720 --> 00:13:20,960
it could signal a turning point.
 
The size of candles matters too.  

147
00:13:20,960 --> 00:13:25,600
Big candles show strong moves.
If you see big green candles with  

148
00:13:25,600 --> 00:13:30,800
small wicks breaking above resistance, 
it implies a strong breakout. 

149
00:13:30,800 --> 00:13:35,160
The same goes for big red 
candles breaking below support.
  

150
00:13:35,160 --> 00:13:39,960
Heiken Ashi candles can also help you 
spot false breakouts. You might see a  

151
00:13:39,960 --> 00:13:46,560
candle break past support or resistance, but 
with a long wick pointing back into the range. 

152
00:13:46,560 --> 00:13:52,920
This could be a fake out. In this case, you 
wait for more candles to confirm the break.
  

153
00:13:52,920 --> 00:13:58,680
Now, support and resistance aren't 
exact prices. They're more like zones. 

154
00:13:58,680 --> 00:14:04,320
You might see Heiken Ashi candles change 
color near a level, not exactly at it. 

155
00:14:04,320 --> 00:14:11,200
The wicks might not touch the exact level, while 
the bodies stay a bit away. This is normal.
  

156
00:14:11,200 --> 00:14:16,880
Also, strong support or resistance 
often gets tested more than once. 

157
00:14:16,880 --> 00:14:22,280
You might see Heiken Ashi candles change 
color at the same price several times. 

158
00:14:22,280 --> 00:14:27,040
You might also see long wicks 
repeatedly touch the same level. 

159
00:14:27,040 --> 00:14:33,040
This repeated pattern can make a level 
weaker, with each test of the level.
  

160
00:14:33,040 --> 00:14:38,880
Sometimes, support and resistance switch roles.
Old support can become new resistance,  

161
00:14:38,880 --> 00:14:43,800
and vice versa.
Again, watch for Heiken Ashi color changes  

162
00:14:43,800 --> 00:14:49,160
and wick patterns at these flipped levels.
They can signal if the level is holding  

163
00:14:49,160 --> 00:14:52,440
in its new role.
 
Time frames matter  

164
00:14:52,440 --> 00:14:58,560
when using these candles to spot key levels.
Higher time frames often show more important  

165
00:14:58,560 --> 00:15:06,131
levels. A color change with a long wick on 
a higher chart might be more significant.
 
  

166
00:15:06,131 --> 00:15:08,280
Heiken Ashi supply and demand
Supply and demand trading becomes a  

167
00:15:08,280 --> 00:15:13,720
lot easier using Heiken Ashi candles.
These candles will help you spot  

168
00:15:13,720 --> 00:15:20,240
key areas where buyers and sellers clash.
The supply and demand zones are like the spots  

169
00:15:20,240 --> 00:15:26,520
where one team suddenly gains the upper hand.
For long trades, you're looking for places  

170
00:15:26,520 --> 00:15:32,000
where buyers (meaning demand) overpower 
sellers, (supply). For short trades,  

171
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:37,120
it's the opposite – you're looking 
for areas where sellers take control.
  

172
00:15:37,120 --> 00:15:42,920
You're searching for big, bold Heiken 
Ashi candles, that really stand out. 

173
00:15:42,920 --> 00:15:49,160
These big candles are like flashing neon signs, 
telling you something important happened there. 

174
00:15:49,160 --> 00:15:52,160
But you don't just want 
the big candles themselves. 

175
00:15:52,160 --> 00:15:59,040
You want to find where they started – their origin 
point. This is where the real action begins. 

176
00:15:59,040 --> 00:16:03,200
Once you spot this origin, 
you'll mark a zone around it. 

177
00:16:03,200 --> 00:16:09,440
This is your supply or demand zone, depending 
on whether price moved up or down from there.
  

178
00:16:09,440 --> 00:16:16,360
Now, Heiken Ashi candles are a bit tricky because 
they start from the middle of the previous candle. 

179
00:16:16,360 --> 00:16:22,560
So, you need a special way to mark these zones.
For a supply zone (where sellers might take  

180
00:16:22,560 --> 00:16:28,920
control), look for the last green (bullish) 
Heiken Ashi candle, before a big drop in price. 

181
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:35,440
Then, draw a box from there, up to the 
highest point just before the drop. 

182
00:16:35,440 --> 00:16:41,200
For a demand zone (where buyers might 
step in), find the last red (bearish)  

183
00:16:41,200 --> 00:16:46,800
candle before a big move up. Draw your 
box from there, down to the lowest  

184
00:16:46,800 --> 00:16:53,160
point just before the price jumped up.
 
These zones come in different flavors: 

185
00:16:53,160 --> 00:16:58,840
First, we have fresh zones: they haven't been 
touched yet. Price hasn't come back to test them. 

186
00:16:59,680 --> 00:17:04,320
Then we have non-fresh zones. 
Price has visited them once. 

187
00:17:04,320 --> 00:17:09,640
And finally, we have used-up zones. 
Price has bounced off them several  

188
00:17:09,640 --> 00:17:16,480
times. They're not great for big trades, 
but might work for quick in-and-out moves.
  

189
00:17:16,480 --> 00:17:20,960
When you're marking these zones, use 
a simple approach. Don't clutter your  

190
00:17:20,960 --> 00:17:27,160
chart with too many zones. Keep it clean 
and focus on the most important areas. 

191
00:17:27,160 --> 00:17:32,840
Try to have no more than 3 to 5 
zones on your chart at a time. 
  

192
00:17:32,840 --> 00:17:37,440
Here's what makes a Heiken 
Ashi zone worth your attention: 

193
00:17:37,440 --> 00:17:44,240
First, the fresher the zone, the better. Traders 
are more likely to still have orders waiting  

194
00:17:44,240 --> 00:17:50,320
in a zone that hasn't been tested yet.
Also, strength matters. Look for zones  

195
00:17:50,320 --> 00:17:58,320
where price left in a hurry. These strong moves 
show a big imbalance between buyers and sellers. 

196
00:17:58,320 --> 00:18:02,480
Then focus on zones near the 
current price. Don't try to  

197
00:18:02,480 --> 00:18:09,800
plot every zone since the beginning of time.
And finally, look for dense zones. Zones where  

198
00:18:09,800 --> 00:18:16,720
price hung around for a while, before making a 
big move, are often powerful. It's like pressure  

199
00:18:16,720 --> 00:18:21,800
building up before an explosion.
 
 
Now, let's talk about how to spot  

200
00:18:21,800 --> 00:18:29,040
the best Heiken ashi supply and demand zones.
First, check out how price left the zone. Did it  

201
00:18:29,040 --> 00:18:34,720
shoot out fast, or did it slowly drift away?
The faster and stronger the move,  

202
00:18:34,720 --> 00:18:39,880
the more likely it is that some big 
players placed heavy orders there.
  

203
00:18:39,880 --> 00:18:45,840
Next, look at how long price hung around 
in the zone. The less time it spent there,  

204
00:18:45,840 --> 00:18:50,560
the more explosive the imbalance 
between buyers and sellers. 

205
00:18:50,560 --> 00:18:57,480
Also, pay attention to how far price traveled 
after leaving the zone. The further it went before  

206
00:18:57,480 --> 00:19:04,560
coming back, the juicier the potential trade.
And again, don't forget about freshness. The  

207
00:19:04,560 --> 00:19:10,000
first time price comes back to a zone 
is usually the strongest opportunity. 

208
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:15,800
Each visit after that weakens the zone a bit.
 
So, how do you actually trade these  

209
00:19:15,800 --> 00:19:21,480
zones? It's pretty straightforward:
For buying, wait for price to touch a  

210
00:19:21,480 --> 00:19:28,200
demand zone, and bounce up with a green Heiken 
Ashi candle. Ideally, this candle won't have  

211
00:19:28,200 --> 00:19:35,760
a lower wick, showing strong buying pressure.
 
For selling, look for price to hit a supply zone,  

212
00:19:35,760 --> 00:19:42,120
and bounce down with a red Heiken Ashi candle.
A candle with no upper wick is better,  

213
00:19:42,120 --> 00:19:46,800
indicating strong selling pressure.
 
Place your stop loss just below the  

214
00:19:46,800 --> 00:19:53,000
demand zone for buy trades, or just 
above the supply zone for sell trades. 

215
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:58,640
As for when to close your trade, hold it 
until price reaches the opposite type of zone. 

216
00:19:59,320 --> 00:20:05,920
So if you bought at a demand zone, you'd aim to 
sell when price hits the next supply zone up. 

217
00:20:05,920 --> 00:20:11,200
Another option is to close part of your 
trade when you see the candles change color,  

218
00:20:11,200 --> 00:20:14,920
signaling a potential shift in momentum.
 
Heiken Ashi backtest 

219
00:20:14,920 --> 00:20:19,080
Many traders ignore Heiken Ashi 
charts because they are unable  

220
00:20:19,080 --> 00:20:24,880
to backtest these candles in Tradingview.
I have a solution for this. This is how I  

221
00:20:24,880 --> 00:20:30,560
backtest price action using Heiken Ashi.
First, open up TradingView and  

222
00:20:30,560 --> 00:20:36,160
look for the chart type selector.
It's usually set to candlesticks by default. 

223
00:20:36,160 --> 00:20:41,840
Click on it and change it to "Line".
This will turn your chart into a simple line. 

224
00:20:41,840 --> 00:20:45,480
Then, you need that line to 
blend in with your background. 

225
00:20:45,480 --> 00:20:49,800
So you need to set the line color 
the same with your background. 

226
00:20:49,800 --> 00:20:54,000
Next, you need to add the 
Smoothed Heiken Ashi indicator. 

227
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:58,600
You look for the "Indicators" 
button, and you add it to your chart. 

228
00:20:58,600 --> 00:21:03,280
Once the indicator is on your chart, 
you'll need to adjust its settings. 

229
00:21:03,280 --> 00:21:08,040
Find the two length parameters 
and set both of these to 1. 

230
00:21:08,040 --> 00:21:13,960
This will give you the most basic, 
unsmoothed version of Heiken Ashi candles. 

231
00:21:13,960 --> 00:21:17,640
And there you have it! Now, 
you can step back and backtest. 

232
00:21:17,640 --> 00:21:24,368
You should see Heiken Ashi candles overlaid 
on your nearly invisible price line. 
  

233
00:21:24,368 --> 00:21:27,760
Volume analysis with Heiken Ashi
Volume leads price. Often, you'll see volume  

234
00:21:27,760 --> 00:21:31,720
increase before a big price move.
With Heiken Ashi,  

235
00:21:31,720 --> 00:21:38,560
these moves are easier to spot and trade.
Think of volume as the fuel that drives price. 

236
00:21:38,560 --> 00:21:45,480
More volume means more traders are active. 
 
So this is how to use Heiken Ashi with volume. 

237
00:21:45,480 --> 00:21:51,200
First, look for trends. Heiken Ashi 
candles of the same color show a trend. 

238
00:21:51,200 --> 00:21:55,640
If you see many green candles in 
a row, it's likely an uptrend. 

239
00:21:55,640 --> 00:22:01,640
Now, check the volume. Is it rising as 
the trend continues? That's a good sign. 

240
00:22:01,640 --> 00:22:08,640
It means more traders are joining the move.
 
Then watch for reversals. Heiken Ashi candles  

241
00:22:08,640 --> 00:22:13,000
change color at turning points.
If you see a red candle after  

242
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:19,200
many green ones, it might be a reversal.
But don't jump in yet. Check the volume.  

243
00:22:19,200 --> 00:22:25,080
A spike in volume on that red candle 
adds weight to the reversal signal.
  

244
00:22:25,080 --> 00:22:32,080
Also, use volume to confirm breakouts. Heiken 
Ashi candles might show a price breaking above  

245
00:22:32,080 --> 00:22:36,320
resistance or below support.
A surge in volume at the  

246
00:22:36,320 --> 00:22:43,680
breakout point makes it more valid.
 
Look for quiet periods. Sometimes, Heiken Ashi  

247
00:22:43,680 --> 00:22:50,440
candles get small. Volume often drops too.
This can mean a big move is coming. 
  

248
00:22:50,440 --> 00:22:58,120
You can also spot accumulation and distribution.
In accumulation, smart money buys quietly. You  

249
00:22:58,120 --> 00:23:04,960
might see Heiken Ashi candles staying in a 
range. Volume might be low or steady. This  

250
00:23:04,960 --> 00:23:11,760
could mean big players are slowly buying.
 
Distribution is the opposite. Smart money  

251
00:23:11,760 --> 00:23:17,400
sells to the crowd. You might see 
Heiken Ashi candles making new highs,  

252
00:23:17,400 --> 00:23:24,440
but volume isn't growing. This could mean 
big players are selling to eager buyers.
  

253
00:23:24,440 --> 00:23:29,960
Very important: don't just look at one 
candle. Watch how they form over time.  

254
00:23:29,960 --> 00:23:36,920
A single high-volume candle might not mean 
much. But a series of them is more powerful.
  

255
00:23:36,920 --> 00:23:44,280
Also, pay attention to where volume spikes 
happen. Are they at support or resistance levels? 

256
00:23:44,280 --> 00:23:51,200
This can be very telling. High volume at 
these points often signals important moves.
  

257
00:23:51,200 --> 00:23:55,560
Here's another way to use this 
method: Look for divergences. 

258
00:23:55,560 --> 00:24:01,920
That's when price and volume don't match up. 
For example, candles might make new highs,  

259
00:24:01,920 --> 00:24:07,960
but volume is dropping. This can warn 
you that the move might not last.
  

260
00:24:07,960 --> 00:24:14,720
These candles are great for showing momentum. 
When they're all one color, the trend is strong. 

261
00:24:14,720 --> 00:24:19,560
But watch out for candles with long 
wicks. These can signal a possible  

262
00:24:19,560 --> 00:24:26,080
reversal, especially if volume is high.
 
You can also use moving averages with these  

263
00:24:26,080 --> 00:24:33,480
candles. When price crosses a moving average 
with high volume, it's often a strong signal. 
  

264
00:24:33,480 --> 00:24:39,160
And don't forget about supply and demand 
areas. When price approaches a key area,  

265
00:24:39,160 --> 00:24:45,440
watch the volume. A rejection with 
high volume is a strong signal.
 
  

266
00:24:45,440 --> 00:24:47,093
Moving averages and Heiken Ashi

267
00:24:47,093 --> 00:24:49,960
Moving averages and Heiken Ashi 
candles work well together. 

268
00:24:49,960 --> 00:24:56,720
First, you see the trend from moving averages.
Then, you evaluate the momentum from Heiken Ashi. 

269
00:24:56,720 --> 00:25:00,160
And together, they help you will 
help you make better trades.
 

270
00:25:00,160 --> 00:25:04,880
Here's how it works:
First, let’s talk about Trend Direction. 

271
00:25:04,880 --> 00:25:10,240
Moving averages show you if the 
market is going up, down, or sideways. 

272
00:25:10,240 --> 00:25:14,520
When price stays above a moving 
average, it's likely an uptrend. 

273
00:25:14,520 --> 00:25:20,960
If it's below, it's probably a downtrend. 
 
 
Heiken Ashi candles make trends even clearer.  

274
00:25:20,960 --> 00:25:25,280
In an uptrend, they'll have 
little or no lower shadows. 

275
00:25:25,280 --> 00:25:29,960
In a downtrend, they'll have 
little or no upper shadows.
  

276
00:25:29,960 --> 00:25:34,080
Then we have trend strength.
The space between price and the moving  

277
00:25:34,080 --> 00:25:40,760
average tells you how strong the trend is.
A big gap means a strong trend. Heiken  

278
00:25:40,760 --> 00:25:44,720
Ashi candles help here too.
Long bodies show a strong  

279
00:25:44,720 --> 00:25:51,680
trend. Short bodies or dojis, (when open and 
close are very close), show a weak trend.
  

280
00:25:51,680 --> 00:25:58,320
Moving averages can signal when a trend might 
be changing. If price crosses a moving average,  

281
00:25:58,320 --> 00:26:04,080
it could mean the trend is shifting.
Heiken Ashi candles give extra clues.  

282
00:26:04,080 --> 00:26:09,320
If you see a candle with both upper 
and lower shadows after a strong trend,  

283
00:26:09,320 --> 00:26:14,760
it might mean the trend is weakening.
 
Moving averages often act as support in  

284
00:26:14,760 --> 00:26:21,000
uptrends and resistance in downtrends. 
Price might bounce off these levels. 

285
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:28,400
Heiken Ashi candles can show you how price reacts 
at these levels. A long-bodied candle bouncing  

286
00:26:28,400 --> 00:26:34,960
off a moving average is a strong signal.
 
When price gets too far from a moving average,  

287
00:26:34,960 --> 00:26:40,560
the market might be overbought or oversold.
It could snap back soon. 

288
00:26:40,560 --> 00:26:46,400
Heiken Ashi candles can confirm this. 
If you see dojis or candles with shadows  

289
00:26:46,400 --> 00:26:52,040
on both sides far from the moving 
average, a reversal might be coming.

290
00:26:52,040 --> 00:26:57,880
The angle of the moving average tells you how 
fast the trend is moving. A steep angle means  

291
00:26:57,880 --> 00:27:05,480
a fast trend. A flat angle means a slow trend.
Heiken Ashi candles add to this. Long candles  

292
00:27:05,480 --> 00:27:12,080
in the trend direction show a fast trend.
Short candles or dojis show a slow trend.
  

293
00:27:12,080 --> 00:27:19,240
When price hugs a flat moving average, the market 
is probably ranging. It's not trending up or down. 

294
00:27:19,240 --> 00:27:24,800
Heiken Ashi candles in a ranging market 
will have shadows on both sides. They'll  

295
00:27:24,800 --> 00:27:30,320
be smaller than in trending markets.
 
Sometimes, price might briefly cross a  

296
00:27:30,320 --> 00:27:35,480
moving average but not start a new 
trend. This is called a whipsaw. 

297
00:27:35,480 --> 00:27:41,280
Heiken Ashi candles can help avoid these 
false signals. If the candles don't show  

298
00:27:41,280 --> 00:27:47,680
a clear trend change, after crossing the 
moving average, it might be a false signal.
  

299
00:27:47,680 --> 00:27:52,680
In strong trends, price often pulls 
back to the moving average before  

300
00:27:52,680 --> 00:27:59,320
continuing. This can be a good entry point.
Heiken Ashi candles during pullbacks often  

301
00:27:59,320 --> 00:28:03,840
have shadows against the main trend.
When they start showing strong trend  

302
00:28:03,840 --> 00:28:09,640
candles again, it might be time to enter.
 
The distance between fast and slow moving  

303
00:28:09,640 --> 00:28:15,920
averages can show market volatility. 
A big gap means high volatility. 

304
00:28:15,920 --> 00:28:22,400
Heiken Ashi candles show volatility too.
Big candles with long shadows mean high  

305
00:28:22,400 --> 00:28:24,880
volatility.
Small candles  

306
00:28:24,880 --> 00:28:31,520
with short shadows mean low volatility.
 
When price gets too far from a long-term  

307
00:28:31,520 --> 00:28:36,800
moving average, the trend might be 
near its end. It's stretched too far. 

308
00:28:36,800 --> 00:28:44,160
Heiken Ashi candles can show exhaustion too. If 
you see smaller bodies or dojis after a long trend  

309
00:28:44,160 --> 00:28:50,080
of big candles, the trend might be tiring.
 
The strongest signals come when  

310
00:28:50,080 --> 00:28:54,280
multiple factors line up.
Maybe price is at a key moving  

311
00:28:54,280 --> 00:29:02,000
average, and Heiken Ashi candles are showing a 
strong trend resume. That's a stronger signal. 

312
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:15,160
Now, if you’re ready for more interesting trading 
guides, go ahead and watch one of these videos.

